GEITA region is facing acute shortage of heads of departments and various units, causing them to be led by unqualified staff. The Geita Acting Regional Administrative Secretary Mr Herman Matemu revealed that to date, a total of 14 departments and 11 units are led by people who do not have the required qualifications. Mr Matemu was briefing the Deputy Minister, President’s Office, Public Service Management and Good Governance Mr Deogratius Ndejembi. According to the RAS, until May 2022, Geita regional secretariat and its six councils had a total of 15,144 staff while the actual demand is 22,773 staff, thus facing a deficit of 7,626 staff. “The staff deficit is equivalent to 33.5 per cent. The sectors which face acute shortage of the civil servants are health and education while it also faces a shortage of engineers, sculptors, surveyors, building assessors, special secretaries, record keepers and drivers,” he said. He noted that they requested for employment permits   from the President's Office which has also been granted in order to curb the shortage. "The region has an area of ​​21,871 square kilometers with five districts, seven constituencies, as well as six councils, with two small towns, 20 divisions, 122 counties, 486 villages, 2,195 neighbourhoods and 65 streets," he said. Deputy Minister from President’s Office, Public Service Management and Good Governance, Mr Deogratius Ndejembi said the government is taking steps to address the shortage of the personnel, noting that they will start with engineers. "In the case of staff deficit, President Samia has approved 32,000 new employments following construction of classrooms, clinics and health centres...we have placed more emphasis on education and health sectors," he said.